
# main-overview

## Development Guidelines

- Only modify code directly relevant to the specific request. Avoid changing unrelated functionality.
- Never replace code with placeholders like `# ... rest of the processing ...`. Always include complete code.
- Break problems into smaller steps. Think through each step separately before implementing.
- Always provide a complete PLAN with REASONING based on evidence from code and logs before making changes.
- Explain your OBSERVATIONS clearly, then provide REASONING to identify the exact issue. Add console logs when needed to gather more information.


Core business system for matching protective equipment to rifle and crossbow scopes through specialized configuration algorithms and validation rules.

## Primary Business Components

### Scope Configuration System (95/100)
Located in `scope-secure/src/lib/scope-mapping.ts`, implements critical matching logic:
- Guard length determination from scope dimensions
- Mount height calculations using objective lens and tube specifications
- Scope-guard compatibility validation
- Special handling for non-standard configurations

### Scope Database Engine (85/100)
Managed in `scope-secure/src/lib/scope-database.ts`:
- Comprehensive scope specifications database
- Scope-specific search and filtering
- Physical specifications to mount requirements mapping
- Brand-specific configuration rules

### Guard Length Management (80/100)
Within `scope-secure/src/lib/scope-mapping.ts`:
- Guard length threshold definitions
- Maximum scope length mapping
- Custom length detection
- Safety margin computation

### Product Configuration (75/100)
Defined in `scope-secure/src/lib/constants.ts`:
- Guard length measurement options
- Scope height category thresholds
- Mount diameter compatibility rules
- Product pricing tier structure

## Business Logic Integration
The system centers on precise protective equipment matching through:
- Scope model specific guard matching
- Complex mounting height determinations
- Custom configuration handling
- Safety-first validation rules

